    "recap_headline": "Troy University Athletics",
    "recap_text": "HATTIESBURG, Miss\n.\u00a0- Troy's clutch two-out hitting and seven strong innings from\nBenjamin Stubbs\nlifted the Trojans to a 6-5 win over No. 12 Southern Miss in Friday night's series opener at Pete Taylor Park.\nStubbs, starting a series-opener for the first time this season, gave the Trojans (10-11, 3-1 SBC) a gutsy performance after the Golden Eagles (17-5, 1-3 SBC) scored three runs in the first three innings, with two coming on home runs off the bat of South Alabama transfer Kyle Morrison while Matthew Russo added a sac fly in the first.\nThe senior left-hander worked seven innings for the third time in his last four starts, allowing five hits and striking out four to two walks. After Morrison's second homer in the third inning, Stubbs worked four straight zeroes, allowing just three baserunners in that span.\nTroy pegged USM left-hander Grayden Harris, who beat the Trojans twice as a starter last season, for ten hits and five runs in his 5.1 innings.\nJimmy Janicki\nstarted the scoring with a three-run homer to dead center in the third, his eighth of the season and fifth in the last six games. Third baseman\nJosh Pyne\ntacked on two runs the next inning with a double in the right-center gap.\nTroy added some insurance in the seventh, as\nBlake Cavill\nbeat out an infield single against reliever Colby Allen to score\nAaron Piasecki\nfrom third. The insurance proved pivotal, as the Golden Eagles tacked on two runs on a Drey Barrett double in the bottom of the eighth, but\nCooper Ellingworth\nresponded in his second inning of work with a 1-2-3 ninth to pick up the save.\nNotables\nTroy's 14 hits were its second most in a game this season.\nThe ten hits and five runs Troy recorded off starter Grayden Harris were both the most that the Southern Miss lefty has allowed this season.\nTroy has used a different starting lineup in all 21 games this season.\nBenjamin Stubbs\npitched at least six innings for the fourth consecutive start. He's gone seven innings in three of those four games.\nJosh Pyne\nextended his hitting streak to a team-high eight games. He's hitting .400 during that span.\nPyne ripped the 65th double of his career, which is the most among active Division-I players.\nPyne went 3-for-5, picking up his third three-hit game of the season.\nJimmy Janicki\nextended his hitting streak to six games. He's hitting .444 with five home runs during that span.\nJanicki launched his team-high eighth home run of the season, which also ranks second in the Sun Belt. It traveled 418 feet with an exit velocity of 108 MPH.\nJanicki went 2-for-5, recording his team-high 12th multi-hit game of the season.\nAaron Piasecki\n,\nBlake Cavill\n,\nNolan Book\nand\nSean Darnell\neach added multi-hit games.\nQuotables\nHead Coach\nSkylar Meade\n\"That's the name of the game. Two-out hitting. When you play over here, it's always a tourney atmosphere. It's two-out hitting, two-out pitching, and playing clean defense. The game really never changes. We have all these different things, analytics and all that stuff. But in the end, can you do things when you need to be clutch?\"\nCatcher\nJimmy Janicki\n\"Every out felt like a regional game. The stakes were high. It was a great team win.\"\nLHP\nBenjamin Stubbs\n\"Early in the game, it was fastball-changeup. My curveball was working throughout the whole game, but later in the game, I found my slider.\"\nNext Up\nGame two between Troy and Southern Miss is set for 2 p.m. Saturday at Pete Taylor Park.",
